Operating Systems – BSc CSIT 4th Semester (Unit‑wise Simplified Syllabus)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Unit I: Operating System Overview (4 Hours)

What is an OS? Core functionalities and viewpoints

Evolution and types of OS

System calls and system programs

OS structures: Monolithic, Layered, Microkernel

The shell and open-source operating systems
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Unit II: Process Management (10 Hours)

Distinguish between process and program; understand multiprogramming

Process life cycle: states, Process Control Block (PCB)

Threads: types, use, user vs kernel threads

Inter-Process Communication (IPC) and synchronization

Implementing mutual exclusion: from busy waiting to semaphores and monitors

Classic synchronization problems: Producer–Consumer, Sleeping Barber, Dining Philosophers

Scheduling algorithms: FCFS, SJF, Round Robin, Priority, Multi-Queue, Real-Time scheduling
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Unit III: Process Deadlocks (6 Hours)

Define deadlock; necessary conditions (RAG model)

Deadlock handling strategies: Ostrich approach, prevention, avoidance, detection, and recovery
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Unit IV: Memory Management (8 Hours)

Memory models: monoprogramming vs multiprogramming; relocation and protection

Allocation methods: fixed and variable partitions, bitmaps, linked lists

Virtual memory and paging; TLBs; page fault handling

Page replacement algorithms: FIFO, LRU, Optimal, LFU, Clock, WS‑Clock; Locality of Reference; Belady’s Anomaly

Segmentation, including segmentation with paging (e.g., MULTICS)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Unit V: File Management (6 Hours)

File system fundamentals: naming, types, attributes, operations, directory structures

File system layouts and directory systems (single-level, two-level, hierarchical)

Allocation strategies: Contiguous, Linked, Indexed, and Inode-based methods
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Unit VI: Device Management (6 Hours)

(Note: While not always detailed in summaries, this unit typically covers the control and handling of devices—assume core concepts covered in standard curricula.)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Unit VII: Linux Case Study (5 Hours)

Real-world exploration of Linux operating system architecture and system management practices
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Pro-Level Summary Table
Unit	Core Focus
I	OS fundamentals & structure
II	Process lifecycle, scheduling, IPC
III	Deadlock theory & resolution
IV	Memory allocation & paging
V	File systems and allocation methods
VI	Device management essentials
VII	Linux OS architecture & insights
